    "title": "Geopolitiks Snacks - May 1, 2026",
    "date": "2026-05-01",
    "tags": ["Pentagon AI", "Classified networks", "Google Gemini", "Anthropic", "Hua Hong", "Export controls"],
    "content": "**Geopolitiks Snacks** - May 1, 2026\n\n---\n\n## 🛰️ The Pentagon invited seven AI vendors onto classified networks and left Anthropic outside the room\n\nMilitary AI procurement has moved from pilot program to guest list management. The velvet rope is now a national-security instrument.\n\n- **The roster:** Reuters reported on May 1 that SpaceX, OpenAI, Google, NVIDIA, Reflection, Microsoft and AWS will be integrated into Pentagon Impact Level 6 and 7 network environments.\n- **The signal:** the Defense Department said GenAI.mil has been used by more than 1.3 million personnel after five months, while Anthropic remains excluded amid the Pentagon's supply-chain-risk fight.\n\n*The classified AI stack is becoming multi-vendor by design, with one very loud absence.*\n\n**Sources:** [Reuters via MarketScreener](https://ca.marketscreener.com/news/pentagon-reaches-agreements-with-leading-ai-companies-ce7f58d9da8bf221) | [Reuters via Investing.com](https://www.investing.com/news/stock-market-news/pentagon-reaches-agreements-with-leading-ai-companies-4652828)\n\n---\n\n## 🎯 Google's Pentagon deal puts Gemini into classified work, with guardrails that read like a negotiation bruise\n\nThe defense-AI compromise is apparently: write down the limits, then also write down that the Pentagon still decides.\n\n- **The deal:** Reuters reported on April 28 that Google signed an agreement allowing the Pentagon to use its AI models for classified work and for any lawful government purpose.\n- **The fine print:** The Information said the contract references no domestic mass surveillance or autonomous weapons without human oversight, but also says Google cannot veto lawful operational decisions.\n\n*Project Maven nostalgia has officially been upgraded to enterprise procurement language.*\n\n**Sources:** [Google signs classified AI deal with Pentagon](https://www.investing.com/news/stock-market-news/google-signs-classified-ai-deal-with-pentagon-the-information-reports-4640272) | [TechRadar on Pentagon Gemini use](https://www.techradar.com/pro/you-dont-cook-a-thanksgiving-turkey-in-the-microwave-pentagon-confirms-department-of-defense-will-use-google-gemini-for-classified-projects-us-military-to-expand-ai-vendors-as-overreliance-on-one-vendor-is-never-a-good-thing)\n\n---\n\n## 🏭 Hua Hong's 7-nm ambitions turned another export letter into strategy\n\nWashington still knows where the semiconductor choke points live. Sometimes geopolitics arrives as a tooling shipment that simply stops moving.\n\n- **The pressure point:** Tom's Hardware, citing Reuters, reported on April 29 that the U.S. Commerce Department ordered toolmakers to halt specific shipments to Hua Hong, China's second-largest chipmaker.\n- **The target:** the report says Hua Hong subsidiary Huali Microelectronics is preparing a 7-nm production line in Shanghai as Beijing pushes to expand leading-edge chip output severalfold.\n\n*The AI race keeps pretending to be about models, then goes straight back to fabs and etchers.*\n\n**Sources:** [Tom's Hardware on Hua Hong restrictions](https://www.tomshardware.com/tech-industry/us-stops-exports-of-chip-making-tools-to-chinas-number-two-chip-maker-hua-hong-and-huali-microelectronics-reportedly-on-the-cusp-of-starting-a-7-nm-fab-in-shanghai) | [Reuters via Japan Times](https://www.japantimes.co.jp/business/2026/04/29/tech/us-companies-china-chipmaker-hua-hong/)\n"
  }
]
